<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-28T16:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-28T16:36:00-05:00" n="563" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d563">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 612.119/644</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Summerlin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-28T15:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">December 28, 1917, 3 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>652. <hi rend="italic">El Universal</hi> recently has claimed repeatedly
                            that the Mexican food commission sent to the United States failed
                            utterly; that no corn is being shipped to Mexico. Although this denied
                            by other local papers, public appears to be in doubt as to the real
                            situation.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Summerlin</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>